1
00:00:00,356 --> 00:00:04,078
When you give your presentation, you need to prove

2
00:00:04,078 --> 00:00:07,407
that your bottom line message is convincing.

3
00:00:07,407 --> 00:00:10,067
You might want to consider ways of being

4
00:00:10,067 --> 00:00:14,103
qualitatively as well as quantitatively convincing

5
00:00:14,103 --> 00:00:19,089
as there might well be data-focused people in the audience.

6
00:00:19,089 --> 00:00:21,179
I was recently on a panel,

7
00:00:21,179 --> 00:00:24,185
and a guy that was on that panel with me

8
00:00:24,185 --> 00:00:25,919
was named Carl Page.

9
00:00:25,919 --> 00:00:27,455
He's actually the older brother

10
00:00:27,455 --> 00:00:29,944
of Google Co-Founder Larry Page.

11
00:00:29,944 --> 00:00:32,360
In fact, Carl mentored Larry Page

12
00:00:32,360 --> 00:00:34,459
when Larry first started Google.

13
00:00:34,459 --> 00:00:36,813
So what, Chris? Why do you mention this?

14
00:00:36,813 --> 00:00:39,514
Well, this was an opportunity for me to ask

15
00:00:39,514 --> 00:00:43,977
Carl for advice on why he and his brother are so successful.

16
00:00:43,977 --> 00:00:46,727
He actually told me that his dad,

17
00:00:47,704 --> 00:00:50,516
who was a great professor in Michigan,

18
00:00:50,516 --> 00:00:54,696
told them that without data to back up a thesis

19
00:00:54,696 --> 00:00:58,279
then it's just an opinion and nothing more.

20
00:00:59,478 --> 00:01:02,395
If you don't have data to back up a thesis,

21
00:01:02,395 --> 00:01:05,209
it's an opinion and nothing more.

22
00:01:05,209 --> 00:01:06,976
I thought that was interesting.

23
00:01:06,976 --> 00:01:11,217
So, please consider finding data to back up your speech

24
00:01:11,217 --> 00:01:14,084
if it's a corporate speech.

25
00:01:14,084 --> 00:01:18,251
I've been trying to be a guest columnist or guest writer

26
00:01:19,570 --> 00:01:22,059
in The New York Times for years.

27
00:01:22,059 --> 00:01:24,657
I keep submitting my articles to The New York Times

28
00:01:24,657 --> 00:01:27,241
but they won't publish it.

29
00:01:27,241 --> 00:01:29,021
A friend of mine told me,

30
00:01:29,021 --> 00:01:32,927
"Chris, it's because you need to have more data"

31
00:01:32,927 --> 00:01:35,835
or proof of my arguments or statements.

32
00:01:35,835 --> 00:01:37,910
I guess this is why I haven't really

33
00:01:37,910 --> 00:01:39,946
been in The New York Times yet.

34
00:01:39,946 --> 00:01:41,534
You gotta have a lot more footnotes

35
00:01:41,534 --> 00:01:44,359
kinda like you do when you write papers.

36
00:01:44,359 --> 00:01:46,026
On a personal level,

37
00:01:47,219 --> 00:01:50,189
my dad reads The New York Times every single day

38
00:01:50,189 --> 00:01:52,997
and my dream is for him to open up

39
00:01:52,997 --> 00:01:55,014
The New York Times one day and say,

40
00:01:55,014 --> 00:01:58,514
"Jackie, look here, Chris wrote an article

41
00:01:59,783 --> 00:02:04,507
"in The New York Times (speaks in foreign language)!"

42
00:02:04,507 --> 00:02:08,090
I guess we never stop looking for approval.

43
00:02:09,729 --> 00:02:11,885
So, data is important.

44
00:02:11,885 --> 00:02:16,196
Any time you can insert a picture instead of boring words

45
00:02:16,196 --> 00:02:19,699
then your audience will be more engaged.

46
00:02:19,699 --> 00:02:22,809
It's like if you're on an airplane

47
00:02:22,809 --> 00:02:25,814
and in the seat pocket in front of you

48
00:02:25,814 --> 00:02:28,717
there's People Magazine or The Economist.

49
00:02:28,717 --> 00:02:30,501
What would you read?

50
00:02:30,501 --> 00:02:32,548
Most people would start off with People Magazine

51
00:02:32,548 --> 00:02:36,174
because it's light, it's more entertaining,

52
00:02:36,174 --> 00:02:38,989
it takes less amount of time to digest.

53
00:02:38,989 --> 00:02:42,968
It's just images and it's fun to look at.

54
00:02:42,968 --> 00:02:45,216
What's really popular today

55
00:02:45,216 --> 00:02:48,138
is something called infographics

56
00:02:48,138 --> 00:02:52,275
which is a visual way to look at data or trends.

57
00:02:52,275 --> 00:02:55,361
Here's a few very simple examples

58
00:02:55,361 --> 00:02:57,694
from the cover of USA Today.

59
00:02:58,852 --> 00:03:02,852
Here's some other examples here of infographics.

60
00:03:03,806 --> 00:03:06,973
News websites are really on a downfall

61
00:03:07,859 --> 00:03:12,321
unless they become much more Pinterest-like.

62
00:03:12,321 --> 00:03:16,018
Visual-based websites are on the upswing

63
00:03:16,018 --> 00:03:19,508
and infographics seem to be replacing traditional

64
00:03:19,508 --> 00:03:23,311
news stories because they're just more fun to read.

65
00:03:23,311 --> 00:03:26,744
Pictures work best, or else we would

66
00:03:26,744 --> 00:03:30,001
take notes on what our kids would say

67
00:03:30,001 --> 00:03:32,480
instead of taking pictures of them.

68
00:03:32,480 --> 00:03:34,665
Do both if you can.

69
00:03:34,665 --> 00:03:39,455
There's a reason why Instagram and Snapchat are successful.

70
00:03:39,455 --> 00:03:43,455
So, we need to adapt our presentation styles too

71
00:03:44,785 --> 00:03:47,505
in order to be more visual

72
00:03:47,505 --> 00:03:51,362
and appeal to all demographics in the long run.

73
