00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:20,417
You get the idea.

151
00:09:21,402 --> 00:09:23,582
There are many ways to get data

152
00:09:23,582 --> 00:09:26,297
or facts for your presentation.

153
00:09:26,297 --> 00:09:28,902
The examples we just went through

154
00:09:28,902 --> 00:09:32,006
can really help you come up with cool ideas

155
00:09:32,006 --> 00:09:34,849
for your presentation as well.

156
00:09:34,849 --> 00:09:37,935
The best way to make it engaging data

157
00:09:37,935 --> 00:09:41,882
is by using interesting charts that are convincing.

158
00:09:41,882 --> 00:09:46,359
Okay, this one's really not that convincing (chuckles).

159
00:09:46,359 --> 00:09:51,274
Citing facts from reputable sources makes sense as well.

160
00:09:51,274 --> 00:09:54,106
"According to the Ministry of Transportation,

161
00:09:54,106 --> 00:09:55,046
"blah blah blah."

162
00:09:55,046 --> 00:09:59,298
This works better than a generic comment like this,

163
00:09:59,298 --> 00:10:00,837
"According to people familiar with the matter,

164
00:10:00,837 --> 00:10:04,286
four out of five Canadians comprises 80%

165
00:10:04,286 --> 00:10:06,831
of the population in Canada."

166
00:10:06,831 --> 00:10:10,998
So just try to have reputable sources like big publications.

167
00:10:12,839 --> 00:10:15,626
Also, try to use at least one

168
00:10:15,626 --> 00:10:19,309
staggering statistic in your presentation.

169
00:10:19,309 --> 00:10:21,623
Steve Jobs actually did this a lot

170
00:10:21,623 --> 00:10:23,185
and of course it worked out incredibly well

171
00:10:23,185 --> 00:10:25,771
for him when he presented.

172
00:10:25,771 --> 00:10:30,504
Use facts to convince people and build up your argument

173
00:10:30,504 --> 00:10:32,504
if it seems far-fetched.

174
00:10:33,436 --> 00:10:36,181
For example, during my TEDx Talk,

175
00:10:36,181 --> 00:10:39,721
which we'll analyze in more detail later,

176
00:10:39,721 --> 00:10:43,185
I tried to convince people that everyone in the world

177
00:10:43,185 --> 00:10:47,352
has as much access, or should have as much access,

178
00:10:48,223 --> 00:10:52,390
to unfiltered internet data sources as food and water.

179
00:10:53,263 --> 00:10:57,079
That, I said, is a basic fundamental human right

180
00:10:57,079 --> 00:10:58,059
we should all have.

181
00:10:58,059 --> 00:10:59,892
I know it sounds really far-fetched.

182
00:10:59,892 --> 00:11:02,202
But I approached it this way

183
00:11:02,202 --> 00:11:05,699
so people didn't just throw it aside as being ridiculous.

184
00:11:05,699 --> 00:11:08,249
Maybe they did, who knows.

185
00:11:08,249 --> 00:11:09,682
But I started like this:

186
00:11:09,682 --> 00:11:13,557
I started by discussing the Berlin Air Lift in 1948

187
00:11:13,557 --> 00:11:18,035
and how the Allied Nations flew literally 200,000 flights

188
00:11:18,035 --> 00:11:20,963
over Berlin in that year, 1948

189
00:11:20,963 --> 00:11:25,002
to drop off basic necessities like food and water

190
00:11:25,002 --> 00:11:29,137
to those that were imprisoned behind this Berlin Wall.

191
00:11:29,137 --> 00:11:31,945
Then later, I spoke about offering

192
00:11:31,945 --> 00:11:34,835
unfiltered access to the internet

193
00:11:34,835 --> 00:11:39,002
as being a fundamental human right, a basic necessity.

194
00:11:40,312 --> 00:11:44,394
Similarly, lawyers use the same convincing tactic.

195
00:11:44,394 --> 00:11:48,606
If you watch TV shows about law or movies about law,

196
00:11:48,606 --> 00:11:52,773
watch how lawyers use qualitative logic to be convincing.

197
00:11:54,463 --> 00:11:58,242
In fact, please check out this epic courtroom scene

198
00:11:58,242 --> 00:12:02,409
of Tom Cruise and Jack Nicholson in A Few Good Men.

199
00:12:03,500 --> 00:12:06,671
It's not too realistic, but you get the idea.

200
00:12:06,671 --> 00:12:10,300
It's entertaining and the content and delivery is superb.

201
00:12:10,300 --> 00:12:11,383
Check it out!

202
00:12:15,430 --> 00:12:19,501
It can't be convincing if nobody understands it.

203
00:12:19,501 --> 00:12:23,721
There's a brilliant man named Rubin Gruber.

204
00:12:23,721 --> 00:12:27,888
He and I were on the Board up at McGill University

205
00:12:30,167 --> 00:12:34,317
for a special startup group called The Dobson Cup.

206
00:12:34,317 --> 00:12:37,535
We would analyze business models from students

207
00:12:37,535 --> 00:12:40,043
and then vote who wins best business model of the year,

208
00:12:40,043 --> 00:12:42,237
that sort of thing.

209
00:12:42,237 --> 00:12:43,776
But I only mention this because

210
00:12:43,776 --> 00:12:46,724
I had dinner with Rubin when I was up there.

211
00:12:46,724 --> 00:12:49,904
He started Sonus and a bunch of other great companies.

212
00:12:49,904 --> 00:12:53,153
He rarely fails; he's so incredibly successful.

213
00:12:53,153 --> 00:12:55,752
So I actually asked him,

214
00:12:55,752 --> 00:13:00,729
"Rubin, why are you so successful? What do you do?

215
00:13:00,729 --> 00:13:02,937
"What's your secret?"

216
00:13:02,937 --> 00:13:04,583
And he mentioned the usual stuff, like,

217
00:13:04,583 --> 00:13:06,828
"I've always done what I've been incredibly

218
00:13:06,828 --> 00:13:08,486
passionate about, I love what I'm doing..."

219
00:13:08,486 --> 00:13:11,863
I drilled down, as I always do, and he said

220
00:13:11,863 --> 00:13:14,693
that before he starts a tech company...

221
00:13:14,693 --> 00:13:15,955
He lives in Boston.

222
00:13:15,955 --> 00:13:18,356
Before he starts a tech company, he flies up to Montreal

223
00:13:18,356 --> 00:13:21,126
and has dinner with his 90-year old mother,

224
00:13:21,126 --> 00:13:23,607
who is not a techie at all.

225
00:13:23,607 --> 00:13:25,604
He says that if she doesn't understand

226
00:13:25,604 --> 00:13:28,528
the business model during dinner,

227
00:13:28,528 --> 00:13:33,348
then he does not invest in the company or start the company.

228
00:13:33,348 --> 00:13:35,412
I thought that was quite brilliant.

229
00:13:35,412 --> 00:13:39,555
It's genius because if not every one understands

230
00:13:39,555 --> 00:13:41,560
your product, you're not going to have many people

231
00:13:41,560 --> 00:13:42,761
want to buy it.

232
00:13:42,761 --> 00:13:46,174
If not many people understand your business model,

233
00:13:46,174 --> 00:13:49,018
you're not going to get many investors.

234
00:13:49,018 --> 00:13:51,971
Actually, when I worked at a large hedge fund

235
00:13:51,971 --> 00:13:55,244
called Citadel, Management would always critique by saying,

236
00:13:55,244 --> 00:13:59,342
"If you can't explain it, then you don't understand it."

237
00:13:59,342 --> 00:14:03,206
You don't have to include all of this when you present.

238
00:14:03,206 --> 00:14:06,269
I just want to save you some time.

239
00:14:06,269 --> 00:14:08,535
So you know where to go if you need access

240
00:14:08,535 --> 00:14:11,822
to stuff online to beef up the arguments

241
00:14:11,822 --> 00:14:14,799
or data within your presentation.

